Package honeyroasted.jype

Interface TypeConcrete

All Superinterfaces:
Type
All Known Implementing Classes:
AbstractType, TypeAnd, TypeArray, TypeIn, TypeNone, TypeNull, TypeOr, TypeOut, TypeParameter, TypeParameter.Placeholder, TypeParameterized, TypePrimitive
public interface TypeConcrete extends Type
This interface represents a Type in the Java type system which is not a declaration. Declarations include class declarations and method declarations, whereas TypeConcretes can be used in various places, such as type arguments, method parameter types, field types, variable types, and more.

    • map

      default <T extends Type> T map(Function<TypeConcrete,TypeConcrete> mapper)
      Applies a mapper function over this Type and its child Types, if any. This method does not walk the entire Type tree. Specifically, TypeParameterized will not apply the mapper to its corresponding TypeDeclaration and TypeParameter will not apply the mapper to its corresponding bound. This is to prevent infinite recursion, and to keep instances of TypeParameter the same.
      Type Parameters:
      T - The return Type. This may cause a ClassCastException if the mapper does not produce a type of T for the highest level Type
      Parameters:
      mapper - The mapper function to apply
      Returns:
      A (possibly new) Type constructed by mapping this Type and its child Types

    • forEach

      default void forEach(Consumer<TypeConcrete> consumer, Set<TypeConcrete> seen)
      Applies a consumer function over this Type and its child Types, if any. This method does not walk the entire Type tree. Specifically, TypeParameterized will not apply the consumer to its corresponding TypeDeclaration. However, this method will apply the consumer to each TypeParameter and its bounds (unlike map(Function)). To prevent recursion if the bounds are circular, a Set containing the visited types is passed to this function and each child invocation of the function, ensuring any instance of a type is visited only once.

      Note that this method is primarily called within the forEach(Consumer, Set) implementation to pass the visited type set to children Types. For general purpose use, forEach(Consumer) should be used.

      Parameters:
      consumer - The action to apply to each TypeConcrete
      seen - The set of types already visited
      See Also:
      • forEach(Consumer)

    • forEach

      default void forEach(Consumer<TypeConcrete> consumer)
      Applies a consumer function over this Type and its child Types, if any. This method does not walk the entire Type tree. Specifically, TypeParameterized will not apply the consumer to its corresponding TypeDeclaration. However, this method will apply the consumer to each TypeParameter and its bounds (unlike map(Function)).

      This is equivalent to calling forEach(consumer, new HashSet<>()).

      Parameters:
      consumer - The action to apply to each TypeConcrete
      See Also:
      • forEach(Consumer, Set)

    • flatten

      default TypeConcrete flatten()
      Flattens this TypeConcrete, simplifying its structure. For example, any TypeAnd with a single element will be reduced to just that element. This may be necessary for checking type equality.
      Returns:
      A new simplified TypeConcrete, or this

    • equalsExactly

      boolean equalsExactly(TypeConcrete other)
      Checks if this TypeConcrete is exactly equal to another TypeConcrete. This requires the same type structure, whereas the normal Object.equals(Object) method on TypeConcretes checks for type equality (e.g., a TypeAnd with one element is considered equal to any type which is equal to that element).
      Parameters:
      other - The other TypeConcrete to check equality against
      Returns:
      True if the this is exactly structurally equal to other

    • hashCodeExactly

      int hashCodeExactly()
      Generates a hash code from the exact type structure represented by this TypeConcrete, wherease the normal Object.hashCode() on TypeConcretes is compliant with type equality (e.g. a TypeAnd with one element will have the same hash code as any type which is equal to that element).
      Returns:
      The hash code of this TypeConcrete's exact structure
